message.content:
This command uses the SSH (Secure Shell) protocol to establish a secure connection between your local machine and a remote server. Here's a breakdown of the command:

1. `ssh`: The basic SSH command used to initiate a secure connection.
2. `-i "~/UserKey.pem"`: This option specifies an identity file that contains the private key for authentication. In this case, it points to a file named "UserKey.pem" in your home directory.
3. `-C`: This flag enables compression of all data sent over the network using gzip.
4. `-L 25900:localhost:5900`: This option sets up a local port forwarding (also known as a tunnel) to forward traffic from your local machine's port 25900 to the remote server on port 5900. This is useful if you need to access services running on the remote server, such as VNC or SSH.
5. `user@ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com`: The user account and destination host to connect to. In this case, it's connecting to an Amazon EC2 instance with the public DNS name "ec2-34-221-131-108.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com".

Overall, this command establishes a secure connection from your local machine to a remote server (in this example, an AWS EC2 instance) and forwards traffic from a specific port on your local machine to another port on the remote server.
